bird.name: Peregrine Falcon
bird.description: Peregrine falcons are among the world's most common birds of prey and live on all continents except Antarctica. They prefer wide-open spaces, and thrive near coasts where shorebirds are common, but they can be found everywhere from tundra to deserts. Peregrines are even known to live on bridges and skyscrapers in major cities.

bird.name: Snowy Egret
bird.description: Among the most elegant of the herons, the slender Snowy Egret sets off immaculate white plumage with black legs and brilliant yellow feet. Those feet seem to play a role in stirring up or herding small aquatic animals as the egret forages. Breeding Snowy Egrets grow filmy, curving plumes that once fetched astronomical prices in the fashion industry, endangering the species. Early conservationists rallied to protect egrets by the early twentieth century, and this species is once again a common sight in shallow coastal wetlands.

bird.name: Canadian Goose
bird.description: Canadian Geese are large waterbirds found throughout North America at various seasons throughout the year. They reside anywhere there is grass, most commonly: lakes, bays, rivers and marshes. The range at which they will live extends from Alaska down to Northern Mexico; although their breeding typically occurs in northern areas of the continent. Their nests are typically close to or on the ground. These birds are most known for their V-shaped flight formations while migrating. Both males and females use a 'honking' call for communication. Their coloration is of a brown body and black necks and heads. They have distinctively long necks and small white patches on the sides of their heads slightly behind their bills. Variations in these features have recently become relegated to sub-families within the species.

bird.name: Hooded Warbler
bird.description: The Hooded Warbler is an American song bird. It is well-known for the boisterous, melodic singing of the males. The warbler is 5.5 inches on average, and has a yellow underbelly with an olive green upper-body. The males of the species has a black hood covering most of its head aside from its eyes. The hooded warbler is typically found in moist, forested areas. These areas range from the north-east United States around Michigan and southern New England and down to the Gulf Coast region. They nest at a low level, preferring shrubs and undergrowth in swampy areas. These birds live off of insects in close proximity.
